<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:31<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720b357682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:31.</label.designator><headtext>Pedigree and family history</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51407a907fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803</cite.query> provides hearsay exceptions for reputation among members of a person&apos;s family by blood, adoption, or marriage or among a person&apos;s associates or in the community concerning a person&apos;s birth, adoption, marriage, divorce, death, legitimacy, relationship by blood, adoption, or marriage, ancestry, or other similar fact of the person&apos;s personal or family history[<footnote.reference refid="Ic59c61b07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] through admission of “records of religious organizations,”[<footnote.reference refid="Ic59c88c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] “mar<page no="339"/>riage, baptismal, and similar certificates,”[<footnote.reference refid="Ic59c88c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] and “family records.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic59c88c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] Such declarations are admissible even though the declarant is available as a witness. <eos/><bos/>If the declarant is unavailable, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-804" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I514201307fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-804(b)(4)</cite.query> provides a further exception for statements of personal or family history.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The use of hearsay to prove pedigree is one of the oldest of the hearsay exceptions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic59c88c37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] General repute in the family is probably the best method of establishing pedigree through the use of hearsay. <eos/><bos/>Thus a witness may testify as to his own age although he has clearly secured his knowledge from hearsay.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic59c88c47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] In general, a witness may properly testify to any fact of family history that relates to the witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic59c88c57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic59c61b07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I5140a1a07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(19), (23)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>As to paternity, see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-serial-number="1972129641" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5140efc27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Simeonides v. Zervis, 127 Ga. App. 506, 194 S.E.2d 324 (1972)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-serial-number="1975130166" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5140efc57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Mincey v. Mincey, 233 Ga. 512, 212 S.E.2d 345 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic59c88c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51413de07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(11)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="339"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic59c88c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51418c007fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(12)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic59c88c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I5141da207fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(13)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic59c88c37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-serial-number="0280312811" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="I51424f507fc011ea988285db8533e975">McCormick on Evidence § 322 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic59c88c47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-serial-number="1884014409" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I5142c4817fc011ea988285db8533e975">Central R.R. v. Coggin, 73 Ga. 689, 1884 WL 2451 (1884)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic59c88c57fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017190" w-serial-number="1952104820" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I514312a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Crawley v. Selby, 208 Ga. 530, 67 S.E.2d 775 (1951)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:31<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
